
const browser1 = await chromium.launch({'channel':'msedge','headless':false});
const context1 = await browser1.newContext();
const page1 = await context1.newPage();

✅ 1. Line-by-line Meaning
🔸 1st Line
const browser1 = await chromium.launch({'channel':'msedge','headless':false});
🔍 Breakdown
const
Declares a variable (cannot be reassigned)
browser1
Variable name → stores browser instance
await
Waits for async operation to complete
Required because browser launch takes time
chromium
Playwright browser engine (like Chrome/Edge base)
launch()
Starts a new browser instance
🔧 Options inside {}
channel: 'msedge'
Opens Microsoft Edge browser
Instead of default Chromium
headless: false
Shows UI (visible browser)
If true → runs in background (no UI)
👉 Output

➡️ Launches Edge browser and stores it in browser1

🔸 2nd Line
const context1 = await browser1.newContext();
🔍 Breakdown
browser1.newContext()
Creates a new browser context
🧠 What is Context?
Like a separate user session
Similar to:
Incognito window
New profile
👉 Why use it?
Isolate tests
No cookies/shared data
Run multiple sessions independently
👉 Output

➡️ Creates a fresh session → stored in context1

🔸 3rd Line
const page1 = await context1.newPage();
🔍 Breakdown
newPage()
Opens a new tab
👉 Output

➡️ A new browser tab → stored in page1


│
├── Context 1 (User A - clean session)
│     ├── Page 1 (gmail.com)
│     └── Page 2 (facebook.com)
│
├── Context 2 (User B - clean session)
│     ├── Page 1 (gmail.com - different login)
│
└── Context 3 (Guest / Incognito)
      └── Page 1 (any website)
